heatre at the Fin de Siècle -- t17 Intergenerational Collaboration and Conflict: Women’s Periodicals at the Fin de Siècle -- t18 Lily Montagu and Liberal Judaism -- t19 American Nervousness: Motherhood and ‘The Mental Activity of Women’ in the Era of Sexual Anarchy -- tIV. Identities: Male -- t20 German and British Sexual Sciences Across Disciplines at the Fin de Siècle: ‘Homosexuals’, ‘Inverts’ and ‘Uranians’ -- t21 The Anglo-African Adventure Novel in the 1890s -- t22 The Fin-de-Siècle Detective: ‘But My Job Don’t End There’ -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tPlates0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the significance of the British fin de siècle in Scotland and Ireland, as well as some regional cities in EnglandThe late nineteenth-century fin de siècle has proved an enduringly fascinating moment in literary and cultural history. It is associated with the emergence of intriguing figures—such as the 'new woman' and 'uranian'; with contradictory impulses—of decadence and decay on the one hand, and of experiment and renewal, on the other; as well as with unprecedented intercultural exchange, especially between Britain and France. The 22 newly-commissioned essays collected here re-examine some of the key concepts taken to define the fin de siècle, while also introducing hitherto overlooked cultural phenomena into the frame, such as the importance of humanitarianism. The impact of recent research in material culture is explored, particularly how the history of the book and the history of performance culture is changing our understanding of this period. A wide range of cultural activities is discussed—from participation in avant-garde theatre to interior decoration and from the writing of poetry to political and religious activism. Together, the essays provide new scholarly insights into British fin de siècle and enrich our understanding of this complex period, while paying particular attention to the importance of regionalism.Key FeaturesContains a re-examination of some of the key concepts taken to define the fin de siècle, such as Decadence, while also introducing new concepts into the frame, such as the importance, at the time, of humanitarianisExamines the significance of the fin de siècle in Scotland and Ireland, as well as in some regions of EnglandExamines how attention to material culture, and particularly to the history of the book and the history of performance culture, is changing our understanding of this periodDiscusses a range of cultural activities, from participation in avant-garde theatre to interior decoration, and from the writing of poetry to political and religious activism  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Jad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurstein, Miriam Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoit, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwor, Richa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEasley, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvangelista, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuy, Josephine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinge, Ina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go